    "summary": "The Dayton Agreement, formally the General Framework Agreement for Peace in Bosnia and Herzegovina, was negotiated at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base near Dayton, Ohio, and signed in Paris on December 14, 1995. The agreement ended the [[event:3677|Bosnian War]], which had killed approximately 100,000 people and displaced over two million since 1992. Negotiations were led by US diplomat Richard Holbrooke and involved the presidents of Bosnia, Croatia, and Serbia — Alija Izetbegović, Franjo Tuđman, and Slobodan Milošević.\n\nThe agreement preserved Bosnia and Herzegovina as a single state within its internationally recognized borders but divided it into two entities: the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina (with a Bosniak and Croat population) and the Republika Srpska (with a Serb majority), each with substantial autonomy. A NATO-led Implementation Force (IFOR) of 60,000 troops was deployed to enforce the military provisions, and an international High Representative was established to oversee civilian implementation. The agreement effectively froze an ethnic division produced by war and ethnic cleansing, leaving a highly complex governance structure that hampered Bosnia's post-war political development for decades.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dayton_Agreement",
